# Cursor Project Config - Portfolio Platform

## Project Intent
- Build a production-ready personal portfolio + blog that can later be reused as a high-quality template.
- Prioritize `apps/web` for active development.
- Treat `apps/admin` and `apps/api` as secondary unless explicitly requested.
- Aim for senior-level engineering decisions: maintainable, scalable, testable, measurable.

## Workspace Priorities
1. Primary: `apps/web` (Next.js App Router, design system, motion, SEO, content experience)
2. Secondary: `apps/admin` (internal tooling/admin panels)
3. Secondary: `apps/api` (.NET backend, domain/app/infrastructure layers)

## Global Engineering Standards
- Always prefer clarity over cleverness.
- Keep modules small and composable.
- Avoid hidden side effects; make data flow explicit.
- Do not introduce breaking changes without migration notes.
- Keep TypeScript strictness high; avoid `any` unless unavoidable and documented.
- Ensure all user-visible copy supports Turkish-first voice while remaining globally readable.

## Web App Rules (`apps/web`)

### SEO-First Development (non-negotiable)
- Every new page must define complete metadata:
  - `title`, `description`, canonical URL, Open Graph, Twitter metadata
  - language and locale consistency (`tr`, `tr_TR` where relevant)
- Add or update structured data (JSON-LD) whenever content type changes:
  - `Person`, `WebSite`, `BlogPosting`, `BreadcrumbList`, `SoftwareApplication`, `FAQPage` when applicable
- Keep internal linking strategy intentional:
  - contextual links between blog, projects, about, and contact
  - descriptive anchor text (no generic "click here")
- Maintain crawlability:
  - update `robots.ts`, `sitemap`/RSS routes, canonical handling, no duplicate path variants
- Use semantic HTML hierarchy:
  - one `h1` per page, meaningful heading levels, proper `article`, `section`, `nav`, `main`, `footer`
- Enforce media SEO:
  - descriptive `alt` text
  - optimized file names and dimensions
  - OG assets per major content type when possible
- Add short SEO reasoning in PR/commit notes for meaningful SEO-affecting changes.

### Performance and Core Web Vitals
- Protect LCP, CLS, and INP on every major change.
- Minimize client components; prefer server components by default.
- Use animation libraries without harming TTI/INP:
  - lazy-load heavy motion when possible
  - avoid animation work on first paint critical path
- Prevent layout shift:
  - reserve space for media and dynamic elements
- Keep CSS and JS payloads lean:
  - remove dead code and unused motion timelines
  - split components by route/feature where practical

### Modern Design and Motion System
- Design language target: modern, premium, creative, calm, and intentional.
- Prefer subtle, meaningful motion over decorative noise.
- Motion must enhance comprehension, hierarchy, and storytelling.
- For GSAP/Lenis usage:
  - initialize only in client boundaries
  - clean up timelines/listeners on unmount
  - gate motion intensity with `prefers-reduced-motion`
  - avoid scroll-jacking and accessibility regressions
- Keep transitions consistent across pages:
  - shared timing/easing tokens
  - unified transition philosophy in reusable motion utilities
- Visual output must remain polished on mobile and desktop breakpoints.

### Accessibility Standards
- Keyboard navigation must be complete and reliable.
- Focus states must always be visible.
- Color contrast should satisfy WCAG AA baseline.
- Respect reduced motion preferences globally.
- Interactive elements must have accessible labels and proper ARIA only when needed.

### Content & Blog Quality
- Blog and project content should be authoritative, practical, and SEO-friendly.
- Use strong information architecture:
  - clear slugs, readable summaries, tag consistency
- Keep reading experience premium:
  - clean typography rhythm
  - code snippets readable and copy-friendly
  - table of contents where valuable
- Encourage topical clusters:
  - connect related posts/projects to build semantic authority.

## Admin and API Expectations
- `apps/admin`: keep code functional, minimal, and maintainable; avoid over-design.
- `apps/api`: enforce clean architecture boundaries:
  - Domain remains framework-agnostic
  - Application layer handles use-cases
  - Infrastructure handles persistence/external concerns
- When backend features affect SEO/content rendering, define contract updates explicitly.

## Definition of Done (for meaningful changes)
- Feature works in local dev for target app.
- Lint/build pass for touched project(s).
- No obvious hydration mismatch risks.
- SEO metadata/structured data reviewed when page/content changed.
- Accessibility basics checked (keyboard/focus/reduced-motion).
- Performance impact considered and called out if non-trivial.
- Code is production-ready and template-reusable.

## Agent Working Behavior
- Start by understanding whether request targets web, admin, or api.
- Unless requested otherwise, default implementation scope to `apps/web`.
- For any new page/section in web:
  1) implement UI/content
  2) implement SEO metadata + schema
  3) validate accessibility/performance basics
- Suggest improvements proactively when they increase:
  - SEO potential
  - visual quality
  - maintainability
  - reusability as template

## Preferred Stack Choices (Web)
- Next.js App Router + TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS
- GSAP (`gsap`, `@gsap/react`) for high-control motion
- Lenis for smooth scrolling when beneficial and accessible
- Keep third-party additions selective; justify new dependencies by ROI.

## Prohibited Patterns
- Shipping pages without metadata/canonical support
- Unbounded animations that reduce usability or battery life
- Ignoring reduced motion preferences
- Large refactors without clear reasoning
- Inline hacks that block future template reuse
